SIMPLE: mosaic
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mosaic
<hw>Mo*sa"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>mosa⟦ium⟧que</ets>; cf. Pr. <ets>mozaic</ets>, <ets>musec</ets>,
Sp. & Pg. <ets>mosaico</ets>, It. <ets>mosaico</ets>,
<ets>musaico</ets>, LGr. <?/, <?/, L. <ets>musivum</ets>; all fr. Gr.
<?/ belonging to the Muses. See <er>Muse</er> the goddess.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Fine Arts)</fld> <def>A surface decoration made by
inlaying in patterns small pieces of variously colored glass, stone, or
other material; -- called also <altname>mosaic work</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A picture or design made in mosaic; an article
decorated in mosaic.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Something resembling a mosaic{1}; something made up
of different pieces, fitted together by design to form a unified
composition.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>aerial mosaic</b></col> <cd>An aerial photograph of a
large area, made by carefully fitting together aerial photographs of
smaller areas so that the edges match in location, and the whole
provides a continuous image of the larger area. Called also
<col><b>mosaic map</b></col> and <altname>photomosaic</altname>.</cd> --
<col><b>mosaic virus</b></col> <cd>A type of plant virus that causes
green and yellow mottling of leaves of a plant. A much-studied type is
the <stype>tobacco mosaic virus</stype>, affecting the tobacco
plant.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mosaic</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mosaic
<hw>Mo*sa"ic</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the style of
work called mosaic; formed by uniting pieces of different colors;
variegated; tessellated; also, composed of various materials or
ingredients.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A very beautiful <qex>mosaic</qex> pavement.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Florentine mosaic</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Florentine</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mosaic gold</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>See <er>Ormolu</er>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>Stannic sulphide,
<chform>SnS2</chform>, obtained as a yellow scaly crystalline powder,
and used as a pigment in bronzing and gilding wood and metal work. It
was called by the alchemists <altname>aurum musivum</altname>, or
<altname>aurum mosaicum</altname>. Called also <altname>bronze
powder</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mosaic work</b></col>. <cd>See
<er>Mosaic</er>, <pos>n.</pos></cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mosaic</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mosaic
<hw>Mo*sa"ic</hw>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <ety>[From
<etsep>Moses</etsep>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to
<persfn>Moses</persfn>, the leader of the <grp>Israelites</grp>, or
established through his agency; <as>as, the <ex>Mosaic</ex> law, rites,
or institutions</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mosaical</ent>⟦br⟧
